==============================================================
  SECURITY FINDING NOTIFICATION  |  F-06  |  LOW
==============================================================

Finding ID    : F-06
Severity      : LOW
OWASP Ref     : API2:2023 — Broken Authentication
API Tested    : ReqRes (https://reqres.in)
Endpoint      : GET /api/users
Date Discovered: Mon, 27 Apr 2026
Analyst       : CrazyCoder

--------------------------------------------------------------
DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------

The ReqRes API provides an authentication mechanism: a POST /api/login
endpoint that accepts credentials and returns a Bearer token. However,
the GET /api/users endpoint — which returns a paginated list of user
records — accepts requests without that token and returns 200 OK with
user data.

The authentication step is cosmetic. The token is issued but never
validated on downstream endpoints, making the entire auth mechanism
non-functional for data protection.

--------------------------------------------------------------
PROOF OF CONCEPT  (Evidence)
--------------------------------------------------------------

STEP 1 — Obtain authentication token:
  REQUEST:
    POST https://reqres.in/api/login
    Content-Type: application/json
    Body: {
      "email": "eve.holt@reqres.in",
      "password": "cityslicka"
    }
  RESPONSE: 200 OK
    { "token": "QpwL5tpe83ilfN2" }

STEP 2 — Access user data WITHOUT using the token:
  REQUEST:
    GET https://reqres.in/api/users
    Authorization: (none — no header sent)
  RESPONSE: 200 OK
    {
      "page": 1,
      "per_page": 6,
      "total": 12,
      "data": [
        { "id": 1, "email": "george.bluth@reqres.in", "first_name": "George" },
        { "id": 2, "email": "janet.weaver@reqres.in", "first_name": "Janet" },
        ...
      ]
    }

FINDING: Token from Step 1 was never required or checked in Step 2.
         User data returned with zero credentials.

EXPECTED: 401 Unauthorized when Authorization header is absent
ACTUAL:   200 OK with full user list — LOW FINDING

--------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS IMPACT
--------------------------------------------------------------

1. The authentication mechanism provides a false sense of security.
   Developers integrating with this API may believe data is protected
   by the issued token — it is not.

2. Token revocation has zero protective effect. Revoking a user's token
   (on logout or account suspension) does not prevent access to /api/users.
   A revoked token and no token produce identical results.

3. The inconsistency is a maintenance hazard. Future developers may
   replicate this pattern across new endpoints, normalizing unenforced auth.

4. An unauthenticated external attacker can enumerate user records from
   /api/users without ever obtaining a login token.

--------------------------------------------------------------
REMEDIATION  (Priority: PLANNED — fix within 90 days)
--------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1: Apply authentication middleware consistently to ALL routes that
        return user data. No exceptions — if a route returns data, it
        requires a valid token.

Step 2: Perform a route-level audit. List every endpoint and annotate
        whether it currently validates the token. Any gap = potential F-06.

Step 3: FastAPI example — apply globally to all data routes:
        router = APIRouter(dependencies=[Depends(verify_token)])

        @router.get('/api/users')
        async def list_users():
            return user_service.get_all()

Step 4: Write automated integration tests asserting 401 for every
        authenticated route when called without a token. Run in CI to
        prevent regression on future deployments.

